In 2019, on the heels of completing my run across the United States, I was introduced to NuCalm, completely changing my understanding of sleep and recovery. 

Many aspects of that 3,175-mile run were dialed in and on point, but recovery and sleep were just afterthoughts. My assumption was that if I ran all day, surely I’d sleep all night. That couldn’t be further from reality. I struggled to find quality sleep and in return spent many days exhausted and riddled with emotional ups and downs.

NuCalm was the missing piece. It’s what would allow me to come down, rest, and reset. It’s a tool that now utilize as an athlete and in everyday life.

Tomorrow at 12pm EST I will be participating in a zoom discussion hosted by NuCalm where we’ll dive into the importance of sleep and recovery. It’s free to join if you’re interested. Just follow the link in my stories. I look forward to seeing you there!

This weekend was rad. Skinning up a mountain and then attempting to ski down it 😅 is a lot of fun. Especially with such great company!

It was a testament to what I hope the next year to be—a year of maximizing my potential by shaking it up and stepping out of my comfort zone—trying new things and incorporating new ideas into my training. 

For years I’ve had quite the basic approach to my running. Run, then run some more. 

In many ways, this plan has served me well. This year, the cracks have begun to show. A few injuries and, at times, low motivation have sent me back to the drawing board. 

By becoming more diverse in my approach to fitness, I know I’ll become a stronger runner and more engaged with it. 

So let the fun begin!

For me, @takethebridge Austin was a reunion of sorts. An opportunity to say hello to an old friend: the streets of Austin. 

These are the streets where I found running and before that explored thoroughly by fixed gear hopping from bar to bar. 

At the start of Take the Bridge, I wondered if I’d remember how to weave the streets. Up Shoal Creek, over on Enfield, down Guadalupe, 3rd and Nueces, all my old haunts and the paths in between. A blast down memory lane. 

Now I head back to ATX for a few weeks. My plan is a little less Town Lake than usual, and a lot more city street runs. If you’re around and looking for some miles, hit me up. I’m down to clown.

📷: @keefshoots

Heading into 2023 like…

Big goals call for big energy. 
Time to turn on and turn it up.

As we all step into the void of 2023 with new intentions and goals in place, I’m reminded of one of the fundamental truths that I learned while running across the United States in 2019. A truth that has helped me to dig deep and push past my perceived limits time and time again. 

It’s what I like to refer to as the arc of difficulty. When we set out on something new or try to leave bad habits behind, we often give up when things get tough. We assume that the thing will only continue to get more challenging when in truth, it won’t. If we continue to push forward and persevere, there will come a time when it gets a little easier and you become more in control of the outcome. 

The first 30 days of my transcontinental run were downright awful. Each mile tested me, begging me to quit, but eventually, things began to get a bit more manageable. I adapted to the task at hand. It never got easy, it still required effort and diligence, but I knew without a doubt I could make it to New York City. This realization has been one of the most impactful lessons of my life. 

A truth we can all refer back to when the going gets tough. Whatever you’re setting out on is worth it, so hold fast and see it through.

January 10th, 2022 • La Lobera 

Happy first anniversary my love. What an amazing year it’s been. 

Forever and always, I’ll be where you’re at. From here to the moon and back.

The Big Bend Ultra is a yearly tradition, a coming home of sorts. With the constantly changing and chaotic nature of life, it's nice to have a fixed annual event. A place to feel the full gamut of time. With its familiarity comes the opportunity to reflect back, check in with the present, and dream about the future.

This year's race weekend was that and so much more. Though, I may be taking the "tradition" thing a bit too far with my 4th consecutive running of the 50-miler and my 4th consecutive 3rd place finish… 🫠

A huge congratulations to Shelley for her win in the 30K and to all the other runners out there. A special congratulations to my man Michael for his first 50-mile finish!

Anyone who knows Shelley and I can attest to our love of food and how conscious we are about what we choose to eat. In a desire to further understand what are the optimal choices for us we will both be working with Ixcela. Through their in-depth analysis of our gut biomes and guidance provided by their dietitians, we are on a journey to maximize our health, performance, and longevity. 

As a 38-year-old athlete, it’s imperative to acknowledge that I am no spring chicken. It’s time I paid closer attention to my overall health in order to maximize my potential and keep pushing distance. Shelley is coming into this from a different angle. For many years, she has struggled  with “runner’s gut” and various other GI issues. 

After our initial consultations with Ixcela, we are confident we will both reach our goals and excited to share with all of you how it goes!

If you are interested in learning more about Ixcela and how they can help you, follow the link in my bio to the “Ixcela” tab and schedule a free 15-min consultation with one of their expert dietitians.

I’ve always been a fan of periodically looking back into my past, chopping up the pieces to better understand the whole. When I do this, I can better navigate what’s in front of me as I continue to progress, evolve, and grow. 

In the past, these times of reflection have predominantly been a process I’ve done in private. Something just for me. Yet lately, I’ve been thinking about sharing these stages and phases. On the one hand, being public with this reflection keeps me accountable to the process. On the other, maybe through sharing some chapters of my past I can help others see that we are all constantly changing and evolving. No matter where we are now, tomorrow will always present an opportunity to move in a new direction. 

I’ve worn many hats in this life and plan to continue changing into new ones time and time again. With each hat I build on what I was before in hopes of becoming more. More well rounded, wiser, and grounded. 

So in the weeks, possibly months to come, periodically I will share a snippet of my past. Some highs, lows, triumphs, and woes…

William Hershal Balenger Sr. or as I called him Papa. 

I have many incredible memories of this man, but the ones that stand out the most are of him and his tractor. Papa cranking the tractor up on a brisk Georgia morning. The slow, low rumble that once ignited seemed to have the power to go forever. Steady, solid, and unwavering. Characteristics synonymous with the man and his machine.

This idea has become a complex motto that helps to shape where I’m trying to get in my training and through this training I strive to embody in my life.

THE SPEED PROJECT - SOLO MISSION
A no rules, no spectators ~ 300-mile race from Los Angeles -> Las Vegas. 

The last few months have been a non-stop soirée of training and planning for what will surely be one of the most action-packed two-and-a-half months of endurance mayhem. 

On March 20th, I will toe the line at this year's Speed Project - Solo Mission, where I plan to do nothing short of RAGE my way through the desert with all sights set on that Las Vegas City Limit Sign. 
 
Once done, the team will rest and regroup for a few days before returning to the California Coast, where @williamgoodge will begin his 64-day crossing of the United States. 

We’ll be bringing everyone along for the journey via Instagram and a real-time weekly YouTube series hosted on @theaudaciousreport channel, with the first episode dropping on April 2nd, the day William sets out from the Huntington Beach Pier.

I’m a big fan of sifting through thoughts and actions in search of their meaning and/or poetic ways of describing them. Once I can identify and put words to a situation or thought, I can use it more effectively. As I prepare for @thespeedproject my thoughts often turn to depletion, the inevitable place one will go during long, arduous endurance events. 

What’s the appeal? Why would one intentionally search for it? 

I’ve found my answer, at least for now:

The beauty of endurance and the inevitable sensation of depletion comes through the ever-swaying pendulum of serenity and chaos. In the faint moments of balance between the two phenomena, this is where the magic happens. This is where we revel and play in authenticity. It’s a place that only arrives after total commitment and follow-through. So when I find it, I’ll be thankful. Thankful for staying steadfast and for the opportunity to explore its depths.

.
Everything that happens is either endurable or not.
If it's endurable, then endure it. Stop complaining.
If it's unendurable... then stop complaining. Your destruction will mean its end as well.

Just remember: you can endure anything your mind can make endurable, by treating it as in your interest to do so. In your interest, or in your nature.
- Marcus Aurelius, Meditations

AUSTIN TX | CIRCA 2011
back when my party was way hard

As I blast west on Interstate 40 en route to the start of @thespeedproject solo mission - 300 miles from LA to Vegas, I’ve been thinking a lot about what version of me will show up at the start line. 

The truth is, it’ll be the same version of me that’s always shown up because there’s not a lot of difference between this guy who used to thrive on Lone Stars, Well whiskey, and a cacophony of uppers, downers, and turn-rounders and the one that now gets his kicks off pushing distance in long, arduous endurance efforts. 

It’s all just a matter of where I’ve decided to focus my attention. 

See, back in the day, my outlet was partying, and I was damn good at it. That’s how I fed the beast. You know, that beast that lives inside of many of us. The one whose growl will never go away. So you have to decide how you want to feed it. I’ve got no regrets about the fun and feed of years past, only pride that when I got tired of feeding it that way, I found a new fuel source. 

So come Monday when it’s time to set off from the Santa Monica Pier with all sights set on Las Vegas, I’ll again rage; I’ll release the beast and let it feed on miles of tarmac and dirt paths.

Rage, rage against the dying of the light.

I’m still processing so much of TSP - Solo Mission.

For now, the easiest and most accurate summary I can scribble is simply one word, WILD. That was fucking WILD.

Also, a massive amount of gratitude and love for my crew. They made it all possible and worth it.

Day 1 of TSP - Solo Mission was a vibe, one continual state of flow.

I could divert the reasons to a good game plan and the previous months' training, but honestly, it was pure stoke that the show was finally on the road and the amazing crew I had around me. 

Having a crew of guys around that were fully present and down to clown was all I needed. We raged through rolling aid stops, not taking a break until mile 80. 

Interestingly miles 75’ish through 100 were on roads I had run on day 2 of my run across the U.S. back in ‘19, allowing my mind to drift back to another time when my running career kicked into high gear. 

I can, without a doubt, say day 1 was one of my favorite days of running… so much so that on day 2, I questioned whether I had used up all my good juju and was destined for a death march of misery for the remainder of the race.

📷: @reece.robinson | @jamestregaskis

Day 2 of TSP - Solo Mission was the inverse of day 1.

After completing the first 100 miles in 20hrs 16min against the advice of my crew, I opted for 100 minutes of downtown, in retrospect, way less than I should have taken. 

So when setting out on the next leg, only 23 hours after having started from The Santa Monica Pier, I couldn’t find a groove. Not long after sunrise, I woke to my feet still shuffling, luckily deep into a large shoulder on the road. Far from traffic, but a first and still a bit alarming. 

Most of the day was spent in a heightened state of misery and exhaustion, contemplating whether or not I had sabotaged my race with the day before’s effort combined with such little downtime in between.

The one highlight was a short section in the middle of the day when @joachimcassel closed in on me, leading to a few miles of toe to toe racing. This moment of direct competition broke me free of the lull of exhaustion replacing it with adrenaline leaving my legs light and my mind energized. In the end Joachim broke away, an incredible display of his athleticism. It was an honor to share those miles with him in friendly competition. 

All in all day 2 was self-induced misery that I hope to have learned from and will try like hell to avoid in the future.

📷: @reece.robinson | @jamestregaskis

Day 3 of TSP - Solo Mission - The day The Weird Turned Pro. 

After a hellish second day, when my pace finally came to an almost standstill, the crew encouraged me to take a whole night's sleep. With so little left in me, there wasn’t a glimmer of protest. I had nothing left to give. 

Upon waking on the morning of day 3, the first words I muttered were “sleep is one hell of a drug,” and so began the march out of misery and where the fun really began. 

The day was spent pushing pace up, down, and around the washes that hug Interstate 15. The crew did an excellent job giving me a heads up to what was coming next, helping to find that path of least resistance. 

The world around me was wild, a psychedelic mirage where my senses were heightened. This, combined with a tired playfulness, allowed me to be carefree and fully present in the experience. Day 3 is why I do this shit. I loved every second of it. 

In the hours before dusk, at an aid stop, a state trooper, seeing the van/camper parked off the road on an overpass stopped by to see what we were up to… the conversation between the officer and my crew would set in motion a tricky/sticky situation that I’m still wrestling with. 

He informed us that 7 miles ahead in the town of Baker, CA, it was legal and permitted for pedestrians to run on the shoulder of the Interstate, being that there is no other right of way between there and the state line… the crew and I were all for it.

📷: @reece.robinson | @jamestregaskis

Day 4 of TSP - Solo Mission Part 1 - Take the Shoulder

Going into this race, the objective seemed simple and arduous. Get from LA to Vegas as fast as possible, with the only parameters being don’t break the law #norules. That’s the message I relayed to my crew, and from there on out, that was our modus operandi. 

Being a seasoned long-distance road runner and having been plucked off Interstate 72 by a state trooper when running across the U.S. in ‘19, I’m well aware that running on the Interstate is a no-go unless in the off chance that it’s in an area where there is no other right of way for pedestrians. In which case, it’s totally within bounds. So when the California State Trooper informed my crew it was legal from Baker, CA, to the state line, we jumped on the opportunity and assumed other runners would follow suit. Around noon on day 4, I got a call from the race director informing me that I had violated the race's rules. I needed to get off the shoulder of the Interstate immediately. For which I did without hesitation. 

I had not intentionally taken a route that was out of bounds. It was stated in the race packet, that I never read, not to run on the interstate, as it was assumed to be illegal. This caveat was one more rule than I expected considering the whole #norules except don’t break the law thing. Nonetheless, I was in the wrong, and the news rattled me. 

In my heightened state of exhaustion, this news hit me like a ton of bricks. The implications for my misstep seemed overwhelmingly damning and just about more than I could handle. I went through about every emotion possible in one hour, settling on frustration and losing all interest in the race. I didn’t care if I kept going or stopped the madness there. I was done. 

My emotions all came to a head when I sat down on the dirt road leaving Primm, just past the Nevada state line. I was wrestling with everything. I was deflated and had no desire to continue. I asked the crew to give me 20 minutes of sleep in the back of the truck. I needed to regroup before deciding what to do next.

Day 4 of TSP - Solo Mission Part 2 - When Rage Turns to Prayer 

I made it about 10 minutes resting when I was startled awake by the truck moving off the dirt road to let another vehicle pass. With this abrupt alarm clock came the notion that the only way out of my conflicted thoughts about the Interstate debacle was through it. I realized that in the present moment, I had no control over what had already happened but only over what I did now. So like many other times in my life, I decided to run my way through it. 

I knew the best thing I could do was show up entirely to the present moment, make no excuses, and give the last 35 miles absolutely everything I had. So that’s what I did. A switch was flipped as I made a simple pack with myself. For the remainder of the race, if I could run, I would, and that became my internal mantra; if you can, you will. 

For the first time, my running came entirely from a place within me, completely on a spiritual plane with no regard for what was happening physically. I was being propelled by something more, from a place of love and gratitude for all the amazing people and circumstances in my life. This, along with @peter_john coaching me through my breath and reminding me to run with my head up and chest out, I was propelled into the sunset, through the dark desert abyss, and finally into the bright lights of Vegas.

Those 35 miles were the most profound of all that I've run. Nothing was left to question; I gave it absolutely all that I had. I turned a misstep into my triumph, and for that, I'm damn proud.

All the thanks, gratitude, and love for my crew. Without them, there would have been no point in any of this. I'll forever cherish the time we raged through the desert, giving it all total hell every step of the way. 

@williamgoodge | @trippedavis | @peter_john | @reece.robinson | @jamestregaskis

Over the last three months, those who tuned into my posts know that I've been working with @ixcelaperformance to help understand what food choices work best for me and lead to optimal performance. Their guidance helped me put a meal plan for TSP and the coming months together while on the road as lead crew for Williams run across the U.S. 

Along the way, the insight gained from their functional gut microbiome testing has helped to shape my food choices for years to come. One of the most significant advantages of their program has been having a well-informed personal dietitian on hand in real time whenever I’ve needed it.

If you're looking to up your performance or struggling with gut issues this program is for you.

A friendship built on endurance.

About three and half years ago, I got a message on Instagram from William asking for some advice as he prepared for his upcoming attempt at running the length of the UK from John O’ Groats to Lands End (JOGLE)—a run in memory of his late mother Mandy who had past a year prior from cancer. 

A quick phone call and stop-over visit to meet in person, at my home in Colorado, on his way to LA led to me deciding to crew him during JOGLE. 

Out of that run grew a mutual respect and strong friendship. While on the road, William told me then that he’d like to run across the U.S. before his 30th birthday, at which point I knew I'd do whatever I could to help make that dream a reality. Now here we are, day 1 of his Run Across the U.S. 

Over the last 3.5 years, I’ve watched as William has grown as an individual and a runner, all while continuing to process and honor his mother's passing with bolder and bolder runs. This is the crown effort with a massive goal of running 3,175 miles in 64 days (50 miles per day) while working to raise $500,000 for cancer charities.

I’m honored to be his lead crew and as proud of him as I could be. William, you’ve got this, and we’re here for you every step of the way. 

At @theaudaciousreport, we will bring you weekly YouTube episodes following effort and antics. The first episode is now live. We hope you enjoy!

📷: @trippedavis

Three days in, and things are running like a top. Will’s been cruising right a long while the crew has worked to find its groove. We're all dialed in now and enjoying the open road as we make our way into the Mojave. 

It's been an honor to pass along tips and tricks learned from my run across the U.S. in ‘19. The most important of these is, at the end of the day, there's always room for a beer, sometimes even 2, but never 3... never 3.

Sometimes you’ve got to stop and take it all in...

Day 4 was a dream. We dropped deep into the Mojave, where cars are seldom and views galore. 

Will continues to impress as he cuts his way through California and we close in on Arizona. 

Crew spirits are high, with no shortage of motivation as we continue to watch our guy do his thing.

Hello Arizona!

Yesterday we crossed the Colorado River leaving California behind as we entered Arizona. State lines are rewarding and monumental milestones when crossing such a vast country.

William continues to press on with strength and high vibes. To say I'm impressed with his performance thus far would be an understatement. It’s incredible to witness and be a part of.

“Teamwork is the ability to work together toward a common vision. The ability to direct individual accomplishments toward organizational objectives. It is the fuel that allows common people to attain uncommon results.” - Andrew Carnegie

Day 10, and he's still cruising. 

William and I talked at length before the start of this run, speculating about how his body and mind would respond to the 50+ mile days. We both had the inclination that due to past challenges, most notably JOGLE, he would be spared the grueling adaptation period one experiences during their first rigorous multi-day endeavor. I'm happy to report that, thus far, we were right. The man is thriving. 

Each day he wakes as energized as the one before gets ready and goes to work. It's an amazing thing to watch and be a part of. 

Onward in a northeastern direction we go.
“Smile, smile, smile at your mind as often as possible. Your smiling will considerably reduce your mind's tearing tension.” - Sri Chinmoy

.
THE NAVAJO NATION

When I made my way across the U.S. in ‘19, I was not expecting the Navajo Nation or what I would find here. There’s an undeniable beauty to this land and its people that lends itself to a feeling of calm and serenity as you make your way through. 

William was aware of how I felt about this portion of the run, though we all have our own experiences and perspectives, and I wanted to hold space for his to be his own. 

Now as we’re roughly halfway through this incredible land, I'm happy to report that his experience and perception have confirmed my own. It’s simply a magical place.

We continue to make our way east through The Navajo Nation. 

Out here, there are few distractions or obstacles to navigate. This simplicity allows for the purest version of multi-day running to shine. 

We wake, we get William on the road, and the remainder of the day turns into a repetitive rhythm, assuring that William is fed, hydrated, and in good spirits and provide company on his afternoon miles. All while taking in this amazing land and getting in as many laughs as possible.

Here’s to the good life!

. 
“There’s a lot of things wrong with this country, but one of the few things still right with it is that a man can steer clear of the organized bullshit if he really wants to. It’s a goddamned luxury, and if I were you, I’d take advantage of it while you can.”
Hunter S. Thompson, Fear and Loathing in America: The Brutal Odyssey of an Outlaw Journalist

Our guy continues to smash it as we all learn and grow out here on the road.

The mountains have found us as we make our way into northern New Mexico. With that comes slower miles and longer days. 

All the love, support, and donations are our fuel so please keep it up.

Cheers to you, William Goodge!

I've seen some impressive displays of athleticism in my day. Yesterday’s right up there at the top of the list.

William woke up knowing it was going to be a BIG day. A day we’ve been anticipating and talking about for months—the climb out of Taos and over to Angel Fire, the highest point on the route.

He smashed it, maintaining close to a 5-mile-per-hour pace all the way to the top. 

Onward we go!

We’ve entered Oklahoma, the longest state on the route. A state ripe full of open and never-ending roads with few turns or changes in aesthetic. The monotony of this section is a very real thing that we all have to do our best to spice up and make as fun as we can, so yesterday's company and the antics that ensued were precisely what we needed. 

I could wax poetically about it all, but sometimes it's best to let the pictures speak for themselves. 

Thanks, @adee_phelan_5 and @thekingofchemo, so much for pausing your incredible journey to find us. It was a day we will not soon forget.

.
“Well, I never been to heaven. But I been to Oklahoma.” - Three Dog Night

Another day closer to NYC.

Oklahoma has greeted us with less than ideal weather though William's taking it in stride.

We make the most of each day, taking it for what it is and pressing forward. Though I'd be lying if I said we are not all looking forward to warmer and dryer days.

Wow, the difference between western and eastern Oklahoma is profound. We’ve transitioned from open prairie into rolling hills and hardwoods. 

The rhythm continues; wake, get Will going, move up 6 miles, provide aid, repeat until mile 36 or 42, set him up for a 30min NuCalm Restore session, join him for some miles, dinner, sleep, and do it again.

.
“If we couldn’t laugh we would all go insane.” - Jimmy Buffett

The miles and states continue to tick by. Today we slip out of Illinois and into Indiana. The mornings are muggy, and the afternoons hot. The weather is a sure sign we’re east and closing in on Central Park. It’s now a balancing act between wanting to be present in the moment while also yearning for the finish.

.
THE 10-DAY COUNTDOWN HAS COMMENCED

Holy shit NYC is just around the corner with one BIG hurdle ahead, The Appalachian Mountains. We’re ready for it.

The last almost seven weeks have been a lot of things. There have been moments of inspiration, frustration, excitement, and monotony, along with many other emotions that I haven't the time to type. 

Through all of these, there has been growth and fulfillment. To be there for another as they take on something monumental, something that most would shudder at the thought of, is worth doing. 

When one puts themselves on the line for the sheer reason of reaching high, all those participating rise as well.

Thank you, William, for being bold. NYC, here we come.

NEW YORK CITY, we’re coming for you!!! I can not believe this wild ride is about to come to an end.

Our guy has absolutely smashed it.

If you’re in or around the city this Saturday morning, it’s an open invitation to come help run William into Central Park. Let’s make it a party. 

Check our stories for details.

.
All the feels. Congrats William.

A massive thank you to @nucalm_official for making this possible.

As I transition from crewing Transcon into preparing for my own races this summer and fall it’s important that I keep things fresh in both spirit and gear. The new @altrarunning Torin 7’s have been a good move. The large toe box and zero drop allows my feet to move freely and naturally. It’s not my first time in Torins but the first time in many years. There’s no doubt upgrades and changes have lead to a more comfortable feel. #altrarunning #ad

Though only two and half months ago, The Speed Project feels like a distant dream. The beginning of so much, a crew green yet ready for the road ahead. A race that brought with it a lifetime of triumphs and struggles. A run that showed me how to continue past my physical limitations, relying instead on heart, determination, and a simple motto; “If you can, you will.”

This coming weekend I’ll again toe the line, though in a much different format, the Sri Chinmoy 24-Hour Race around a ~3-mile loop at Rockland State Park just north of NYC. With this format change, I hope to explore the heart side of running further. I’m interested in what happens when one removes the variable of terrain. How much faster does the heart take over? A concept I assume this race will only begin to scratch the surface of yet something I hope to continue exploring further. 

* a huge thank you to my dear friend and brother @trippedavis for these photos that he was able to take while also crewing for those wild three and half days through the desert. A series of photos that I will forever cherish.

“Sometimes you're flush and sometimes you're bust, and when you're up, it's never as good as it seems, and when you're down, you never think you'll be up again, but life goes on.” - Fred Jung, Blow

This quote quite accurately sums up my experience at the Sri Chinmoy 24-hour race this weekend. Things were FLUSH; I was enjoying every loop, moving efficiently, taking in the beautiful 3-mile loop until things went BUST around 8 hours (~51 miles) in, when nausea took over, and I began vomiting. The next 11.5 hours were a blur of mitigation tactics made by Shelley and me to overcome the nausea and vomiting. Unfortunately, I couldn’t kick the combo, so at 19 hrs and 39 min with 100 miles down; I called it a day… Well, day and ¾ of a night, but who’s counting.

Saturday, one of my biggest dreams/fears came true while out on the run. 

I SAW A MOUNTAIN LION!!! 

Seeing such an elusive yet powerful creature up close was something I’ve often imagined, and the emotions it evoked didn’t disappoint. It was huge and close enough to make the hair on the back of my neck stand up. Close enough that all I could do was freeze and take it in. 

At that moment, I was initially in awe and terrified. However, the terror was quickly replaced with adrenaline. It's an incredible feeling to understand one’s vulnerability in the hierarchy of nature so tangibly. 

That cat had the upper hand, and my fate was at the mercy of nothing more than primal instinct… fuckin’ hell, what an incredible feeling!!!

For those who have watched The Colorado Crush you might remember that in the final leg of the challenge, The Leadville 100, I nearly fell apart. If it wasn’t for Sam, who at the time was an absolute stranger, I’m not sure I would have made it back over Hope Pass and on to finish the race and subsequently the larger goal of The Colorado Crush. 

This Saturday night and into Sunday morning, I was finally able to repay the favor by pacing him from Twin Lakes to the finish of his 5th Leadville 100 Finish. 

It wasn’t his most straightforward finish, requiring a lot of grit to overcome immense nausea and fatigue induced by the mid-day heat but he got it done, and I couldn’t be more proud of him.

Cheers to you, Sam. I’m honored to call you a friend and thanks for helping out a perfect stranger two years ago. You're the epitome of what I love about the trail community.

Lately, I’ve been joking to myself about how I should quit saying I’m going for a run and instead say I’m going for a think. 

Running, for me, is a whole experience of mind, body, and soul. Every ounce of me gets something from the practice. One facet constantly feeds the next. 

At times, I run to feel my best physically, at others to awaken my heart, and in phases of life such as now, to sift through thoughts that turn into ideas and on into action. 

The intertwined nature of these three facets has propelled my life in new and exciting directions that I often never saw coming. 

I cannot nor want to imagine where my life would be without it. So today, I give thanks to the gods of running. Your path has lit my way for almost a decade now, and for this, I’m eternally grateful.

When embarking on my running journey a decade ago, I never imagined where it would take me. From those first miles to conquering the expanse of the United States and more, it’s been a wild ride. My approach has always been about pushing distance, not speed. The marathon was simply a stepping stone in my quest for endurance.

But lately, a new challenge has enticed me: THE MARATHON. As I dive deeper into the running world, I can't help but wonder about my potential in this unexplored territory. It's time to find out just how fast I can go. I’m ready to chase a new kind of thrill… where’s my edge at 26.2?

In my pursuits to leave no stone unturned and fully embrace this unknown, for the first time, I’m looking to the guidance of a coach (@jdcunningham97). Having someone much more knowledgeable take the reins of my trajectory is a great feeling, leaving me with no excuses and the responsibility of doing the work.

What an amazing experience. Few things have ever humbled me as much as breaking trail through deep powder. How small and vulnerable I felt summiting a pass with the wind whipping as well as the first time hearing the whumpf of snowpack settling under my feet. A sensation only rivaled by the strength and vastness of the open ocean. 

An experience I’ll never forget.
